  "prompt": "How long can I stay outside the UK as a dependant of the tier2 visa?",
  "response": "As a dependant of a Tier 2 visa holder, you are generally allowed to stay outside the UK for up to 180 days (approximately 6 months) per year without affecting your visa status. However, there are some important considerations:\n\n1. The 180-day limit is cumulative and applies to the entire year.\n\n2. Staying outside the UK for longer than 180 days may:\n- Potentially impact your ability to apply for settlement (indefinite leave to remain)\n- Affect your continuous residence requirement\n- Potentially lead to visa complications\n\n3. If you need to stay outside the UK for longer than 180 days, you should:\n- Consult with the Home Office\n- Discuss your specific circumstances with an immigration lawyer\n- Consider applying for a re-entry visa\n\n4. Your main visa holder (the Tier 2 visa principal applicant) may have different rules about time outside the UK.\n\n5. Always keep documentation of your travels and reasons for extended absence.\n\nFor the most current and personalized advice, it's recommended to:\n- Check the latest UK immigration rules\n- Consult with the Home Office\n- Seek advice from an immigration specialist",
